I think the role of Kazakhstan (non-OPEC, supporting Russia's stance) and Iraq (OPEC, over-production after the past meeting likely) is underestimated. This could again end up in a OPEC/non-OPEC volume/market share/price war.
With monthly meetings the urgency to raise is lower. Saudis are on convincing mode and lower oil price today makes it easier

Talks adjourned until the 5th, on the basis that the Saudis could still win the argument, but allow Russia to save face by allowing a small increase, I am leaving that as the favoured outcome, but without much conviction (56/44).
With Saudi Arabia opposed and digging their heels in, I think there is unlikely to be an increase.

Jan 4th Today’s meeting adjourned without consensus being met. Opening comments from S.A. oil minister urged prudence and restraint (see below) and sources report that most countries now favour continuing current output ceilings. Russia and Kazakhstan still want to increase by 500k bpd, however, UAE have changed their stance, and now support a rollover. Iraq, Nigeria also support rollover.

Price momentum positive due to US stimulus package, positive vaccine news and non-OECD development - global inventories falling slightly and market has capacity for increase supply without this pulling the price down. Russian stance clear (upward); UAE, Nigeria (big trade deficit) and Iraq seem to favour increase. S.A. unclear. Upgrading probability of production being adjusted upward significantly to 70.

World economy not yet ready to assume an increase in oil prices. As soon as jobs, airlines, and other activities return to a certain normality then OPEC may think to adjust prices. On the other side if not adjustments, then no sense to held a meeting.
I am surprised by the strength of the consensus here given the only thing cited seems to be Russia’s public statements.

The next OPEC+ meeting is scheduled for tomorrow (January 4th, https://www.opec.org/opec_web/en/press_room/6267.htm), so there's only an outside chance it's not held before the 1st of February. With oil prices continuing to increase after the upwards adjustment agreed December 3rd (https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/cmjpj223708t/oil), a downwards adjustment seems almost as unlikely.
The next OPEC + meeting ii Mon, Jan 4 by video conference - https://bit.ly/353fjjS
Consensus is lacking , therefore no point to meet.

Price is rising well, and has been throughout December. Although demand is forecasted to be slightly lower, there is also significant pressure from member nations to increase production (notably Nigeria who are operating a significant trade deficit due to lower oil production) and this is in light of recent further news re C19 vaccines (notable AstraZeneca on Dec 30th). A further increase from Feb is supported by Rus provided prices are stable and within a 45 - 55 USD range. Moreover, increasing production by <= 500k b/pd shouldn't pull prices down, but will be helpful to member nations and a step towards the 2m b/pd April target.

Updating as we are close to the meeting date. No news indicating the meeting won't happen so downgrading to 1. Oil price has continued to be stable and moving higher, and Russia still wants to adjust production upward, so downgrading downward production to 0. It also looks like I misinterpreted the media reports about the meeting, the official press release (https://www.opec.org/opec_web/en/press_room/6257.htm) seems to suggest that the burden of proof lies with those countries that don't want a production increase, so moving upward production to 80 and the no change to 19.

Unless prices collapse, another 500,000 barrel increase seems to have already been agreed on.

There is around 5 mb/d of spare capacity idle in OPEP, so there is a big incentive to put that production back into the market as soon as possible. At $50 + Brent prices OPEP it is a good price to sell as much as possible. On top of that apparent demand is going down , so that is an extra incentive to sell more oil at this prices before it goes down again.
Stable oil prices means Russia is keen to get revenue in

I guess it is too early after new year, nothing happens first month and also situation with vaccine is still not completely clear. However, it is stated 4th Jan on opec website. So probably it will happen. Vaccine status is still "in progress", dont think everyone will be vaccinated till April 2021. So demand will not increase and hence production will still be cut. Why not further decrease? I guess because oil price is stable.

Russia wants an increase in February. Iran is looking to increase strategic ties with Russia to shore up against potential sanctions from US. The OPEC meeting will occur before January 20th, making a 'wait and see' approach the most likely.
Crowd Wisdom until I do research
Will lean towards inaction and wait and see.

Given how difficult the last meeting was to agree, the next meetings proximity as well as the fact that the oil price has climbed roughly 6% since, there appears to be no reason to reduce production downwards (2%). Postponing the meeting by more than a month, seems to make little sense either as even difficult meetings get postponed by only a few days historically (2%) There clearly is a chance they want to try and tweak the production upward by a small amount again given the price rise, and those that were arguing for a bigger increase in their last meeting will have had their hand strengthened, so will allocate 30% chance there (not higher as the last meeting was difficult). Which leaves 64% that they leave production unchanged.

Looks like Saudi Arabia wants to hold the production at current level while Russia & UAE want to increase the production [1]. Nobody will be able to make the case for decreasing the production as the prices are up over last 30 days.

Most likely production will be adjusted upward to please countries already reeling from the fiscal costs of COVID-19, commodity prices are slowly rising and OPEC will be confident they can raise production without dramatically affecting price
too early for bounceback demand increases

Given the increase at the December meeting and OPEC recent downgrade in their 2021 forecast, it is very likely that OPEC will hold steady at its Jan21 meeting. The second most likely choice would be a small increase in production. This will especially be likely if vaccine rollouts continue at a robust pace and the global economy begins to see an uptick in demand in early 21. However, these impacts would likely not been seen until at least late Feb or Mar. It is likely that ministers would cancel their meeting if it appears things have not begun to pick up or are detoriating. Given the December increase, OPEC will look for any option to not cut output again.
The demand would be sapped by the surge of covid cases. Further increase in oil price would stimulate shale production. other commodity prices falls.

Looking at the 2021 oil report from december 2020 and the 12th ONOMM press release from OPEC I Expect either a small increase, like in December, or no decision before januari 2021. I also allow for the possibility of no meeting January 2021. I suspect a small increase or no decision based on the ONOMM press release stating the intention to "gradually return 2 mb/d, given consideration to market conditions." The report points to monthly ministerial meetings at which production increase for the next month will be decided "being no more than 0.5 mb/d." Given the recent rally in oil prices, and the commitment to raise production gradually, I give a 10% point advantage to a production increase. I suspect a very small change of a decrease, if the economic forecast for 2021 take a turn for the worst. There is also a small change of no meeting before februari 2021 even though the commitment was made during the 12th OPEC meeting.
These oil producing countries have showed a tendency to shoot themselves in the foot so the probability of no decision or increase production is high.

Futures oil prices indicate increased optimism for expanded global economic growth following approval of Covid-19 vaccines and the start of vaccinations in UK & US and expected in EU in the coming days. however, in reality, the bulk of the world's population is unlikely to see vaccination before Q3-Q4 2021. The spread of new Covid-19 cases in the northern hemisphere has lead to restrictions and stronger lockdowns that were in excistance a month ago. This will impact both land and air based transport and hence oil demand.
Notes from OPEC meeting in Dec 2020 (https://www.opec.org/opec_web/en/press_room/6257.htm) indicate a commitment to gradually raise oil production ('paragraph' 7).
The OPEC Member That Could Derail The Production Cut Plan

I believe OPEC will decide to delay their decision until at least Mar or Apr regarding increasing oil output. This will allow for increased future and current prices as COVID vaccine news propels economic recovery globally.
